                                                                                                                       7                                      Pakistan cricket and its recent troubles
                      
	1994: The then Pakistan captain Salim Malik was accused of trying to bribe Australian players Shane Warne and Mark Waugh for deliberately underperforming.         
	May, 2000: Salim Malik and Ata-ur-Rehman found guilty of match-fixing and banned for life.         
	May, 2003: Shoaib Akhtar was caught while tampering with the ball during a tri-series match in Sri Lanka and was subsequently banned.         
	August, 2006: Umpire Darrel Hair accuses the Pakistan team, led by Inzamam-ul-Haq, of tampering with the ball during the Oval Test. Pakistan players walk-out and forfeit the Test match.         
	October, 2006: Shoaib Akhtar and Mohammed Asif sent home from the Champions Trophy in India after testing positive for a banned substance.         
	April, 2007: Pakistan coach Bob Woolmer found dead in his hotel room in Jamaica, after Pakistans shocking exit from the World Cup.         
	September, 2007: Shoaib Akhtar and Mohammed Asif involved in a dressing room brawl resulting in the former being sent home yet again from South Africa just prior to the inaugural ICC World T20.         
	May, 2008: Mohammed Asif detained at the Dubai airport for possession of drugs.         
	January, 2010: Shahid Afridi banned for two ODIs after being caught trying to scuff up the seam.         
	March, 2010: Following a disastrous tour of Australia, PCB bans former captains Younus Khan and Mohammed Yousuf, for an indefinite period. Another former captain Shoaib Malik and Rana Naved-ul-Hasan were banned for one year and fined heavily. The bans of Shoaib, Yousuf and Rana Naved were later lifted.         
	May, 2010: Pakistan leg-spinner Danish Kaneria and his Essex teammate Mervyn Westfield were detained by cops following an investigation into betting irregularities but were not charged.         
	August, 2010: Mohammed Asif and Mohammed Aamer are accused of deliberately bowling no balls as a part of spot fixing deal during the Lords Test.           COMPILED BY MOHANDAS MENON                                                                                                                 
